C â†’ Check constraints (n, values, memory)
B â†’ Brute force first
O â†’ Optimize with known patterns
D â†’ Dry run with small input
C â†’ Complexity analysis
E â†’ Edge cases


âœ¨ Conclusion
--> Solving DSA problems becomes much easier when you follow a structured approach. 
--> The universal formula U-C-B-O-D-C-E (Understand â†’ Constraints â†’ Brute Force â†’ Optimize â†’ Dry Run â†’ Complexity â†’ Edge Cases) helps you stay systematic and confident, no matter the topic (Arrays, Stacks, Queues, Linked Lists, Trees, Graphs).

Key mindset:
--> First understand the problem (donâ€™t rush into coding).
--> Always think of the brute force approach as a baseline.
--> Identify patterns and optimize step by step.
--> Never skip edge cases and complexity analysis.

